{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72dbe273-ca6c-44db-88c6-adbf272a8967","content":"Three EF Core 10 breaking changes directly hit your scenario:\n\n## 1. Azure SQL defaults JSON columns to `json` instead of `nvarchar(max)`\n\nWith `UseAzureSql()`, EF Core 10 changes the default store type for primitive collections and owned types mapped to JSON from `nvarchar(max)` to the native `json` type. Running `migrations add` will generate `AlterColumn` operations for every JSON-mapped property (including your `string[] Tags`).\n\n**Mitigation** — either accept the migration, or pin the old type:\n\n```csharp\nentity.Property(e => e.Tags).HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\");\n```\n\n## 2. `OPENJSON` behavior changes with `json`-typed columns/parameters\n\nYour `.Contains()` queries over `List<int>` currently emit `OPENJSON` against `nvarchar(max)` parameters. Once columns/parameters switch to the native `json` type, `OPENJSON` returns `json`-typed values instead of `nvarchar`, which can cause implicit conversion differences and query-plan changes. Test for correctness and performance regressions after migrating.\n\n## 3. `dotnet ef` requires `--framework` when multi-targeting\n\nWhen a project targets both `net9.0` and `net10.0`, EF Core 10 tooling will **fail** if you run `dotnet ef migrations add` without `--framework`. You must specify which TFM to use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet ef migrations add MyMigration --framework net10.0\n```\n\n---\n\n**Recommended migration order:** pin `--framework` in your scripts first, then run `migrations add` to inspect the generated `AlterColumn` operations, and validate your `.Contains()` queries against the new JSON semantics before deploying.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b309cf88-07cd-4fa6-bd32-52432319ace1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about EF Core 10 breaking changes that affect their specific scenario. Let me analyze their situation:\n\n1. They use `UseAzureSql` (Azure SQL provider)\n2. They ha